One way to prepare is to study and draw lessons from the 1930s.
This meant, that in the worst global crisis “no one was in charge”, according to Charles Kindleberger in his history of the Great Depression.
What seemed to be a gain in a single country was still a loss for the global system.
In the US, class struggle increased rapidly in 1934, after an initial period in which the crisis stunned workers.
This underlines the serious and decisive task to build worker’s organizations and parties that can achieve victory and abolish capitalism.